	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Allocation of tuna-fishing opportunities discussed by RFMOs </h1>

			
			<h4>
												30 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Pacific Islands Forum Fisheries Agency (FFA) hosted an international workshop on RFMO (regional fisheries management organisation) management of tuna fisheries in Brisbane (Australia) in late June 2010. The main purpose was to recommend measures to ensure the long-term sustainability of the world’s tuna fisheries, by addressing the core issues of allocating fishing opportunities within the tuna RFMOs, the management of harvesting capacity in a way that retains the profitability of the world’s tuna fleet and accommodates the rights and entry of developing coastal states, in particular small island developing states, territories, and states with small and vulnerable economies into these fisheries, and the means to achieve that, including the orderly transition of fishing effort and capacity.</p><p>Earlier, in May, the chairman of the Western and Central pacific Fisheries Commission (WCPFC), the largest RFMO dealing with the conservation and management of tuna, stated that more progress was needed, as fish stocks continue to decline in the face of over-fishing: ‘It seems to me that this is due to two factors. The first problem is the reluctance of many RFMOs, including WCPFC, to follow clear and unambiguous scientific advice to reduce catches, notwithstanding that such scientific advice is provided through the mechanisms established by the RFMO itself ... it is simply unacceptable for RFMOs to continue to disregard the advice that is given to them for reasons of political expediency or to accommodate new entrants into the fishery’. </p><p>He continued ‘the main problem, however, is that the obligations to comply with the management measures adopted by the RFMOs rest not on the RFMO but on the states members themselves…. A small number of fishing countries – Japan, the EU, the United States, Korea, the fishing entity of Chinese Taipei and, increasingly, China – are members of all RFMOs. Therefore, it is these states that must bear the primary responsibility for the failure of RFMOs to achieve conservation objectives ... It is also important to note that in taking such enforcement action, states are not only responsible for vessels flying their flags, but also cannot ignore the actions of their nationals, whatever flag they are using. Unfortunately, it is all too readily apparent that in many cases, the nationals of major fishing states use vessels flagged to other states to avoid their responsibilities - the states of which these individuals are nationals, take little or no action to constrain their activities’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Meeting documents, FFA-hosted Kobe Workshop on RFMO Management of Tuna Fisheries, 29 June - 1 July 2010, Brisbane</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ffa.int/kobe2" target="_self">http://www.ffa.int/kobe2</a></p><p>Statement of the Chairman of the Western and Central Pacific Fisheries Commission, UN Fish Stocks Review Conference, May 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.wcpfc.int/news/2010/statement-mr-satya-n-nandan-chairman-western-and-central-pacific-fisheries-commission" target="_self">http://www.wcpfc.int/news/2010/statement-mr-satya-n-nandan-chairman-west...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The management of tuna-fishing capacity, and the subsequent allocation of fishing possibilities, is probably the most difficult issue that tuna RFMOs will have to address in the future. As highlighted by the WCPFC chairman, fishing states, including the EU, have a primary responsibility to ensure their vessels, and their nationals, whatever flag they take, engage only in responsible fishing operations. In that light, the new EU IUU regulation, which allows the EU to take actions against EU vessels and nationals engaged in IUU fishing, is going in the right direction. However, both fishing states and developing coastal states, many of which aspire to develop their own tuna-fishing capacity, will have to find a way to make space for new entrants - developing coastal states- whilst ensuring that the overall capacity is not excessive. It is worth noting that Japan, the EU, the USA, Korea, the fishing authority of Chinese Taipei and, increasingly, China – are members of almost all RFMOs.</p>
		</div>
		
